[b]Predictability Regime Index[/b] answers one question: does the current market reward following momentum, or fading it back to the mean?

[b]What it does[/b]

Instead of guessing whether "trend" or "range" logic applies, the index fuses four statistical predictability sensors — Variance Ratio, return autocorrelation, a Hurst exponent approximation, and a fractal efficiency ratio — into a single signed reading. Positive values favor momentum/trend-following behavior, negative values favor mean-reversion, and values near zero indicate a random-walk / noise regime where neither approach has an edge.

[b]Sensors[/b]

[list]
[*][b]Variance Ratio[/b] — compares k-period return variance to the random-walk expectation across three horizons
[*][b]Autocorrelation[/b] — correlation of consecutive returns; positive means moves tend to continue, negative means they tend to reverse
[*][b]Hurst exponent approximation[/b] — rescaled-range proxy for how persistent the price path is
[*][b]Fractal efficiency[/b] — how directly price travels versus how much back-and-forth noise it produces
[/list]

[b]Reading it[/b]

[list]
[*]PRI above +25 with confidence above 35% — momentum/trend-following regime
[*]PRI below −25 with confidence above 35% — mean-reversion regime
[*]PRI near zero, or low confidence — noise regime, avoid both playbooks
[/list]

Confidence rises when the underlying sensors agree with each other, and falls when they conflict — a strong-looking reading built on disagreeing sensors is down-weighted rather than trusted.

